<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Why the Government's Judicial Review Reform Consultation should matter to you - and those you represent</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:24pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bindmans</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> LLP (LAI 0058)</span></p><p style="margin:24pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">On 9 April 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the Government launched its ‘Transforming Legal Aid’ consultation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> on 5 and 6 September, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">(‘Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps’; ‘Judicial Review: proposals for further reform’) </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the Government announced its intention to press on with the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> main proposals for reform of civil legal aid.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he Committee has indicated it is concerned about f</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">our particular elements of the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">se proposals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">: curtailing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> prisoners’ </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">legal aid; the residence test;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> funding for judicial reviews pre-permission</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and removal of l</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">egal aid for cases with “borderline” prospects of success. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">What follows </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">focusses</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> only on these areas. It should be noted that we have ongoing concerns about ma</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y other aspects of the proposals for both criminal and civil work.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">One of the difficulties wit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">h the proposals is that there are no examples given of the kinds of cases that will be left without Legal Aid if they are implemented. Drawing on our experience as one of this country’s most respected firms</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">undertaking </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, we have sought to provide examples </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">assist the Committee. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">We apologise that this </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">has led to our evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">significantly exceeding</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the Committee’s recommended word limit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for submissions</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Dangerous in practice </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">As the title of this </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">document</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> indicates, we</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> consider the proposals are dangerous in practice and wrong in principle.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The dangers are threefold</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">First, the proposals are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">impractical</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">; they will simply not achieve the Government’s stated aim, to “</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">boost public confidence in and reduce the cost of the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid system</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">” by promoting “efficiency”. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">To take one example discussed in more detail below, the residence test is to be applied to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">729,483 acts of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">civil Legal Aid </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">assistance</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">annually regardless of urgency or people’s ability to prove they satisfy it. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Secondly, if they are implemented, there will be significant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">additional costs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to the Legal Aid fund and to the public purse, even in the short term. To the extent the proposals are intended to save money, they will be counterproductive. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Thirdly, they </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">destabilise </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">the market for the provision of specialist civil legal aid services</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and disincentive firms fr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">m undertaking this work. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Wrong in principle</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">As to principle, there is no doubt that what is proposed fundamentally undermines t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">wo </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">basic features of the English legal system: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">he rule of law</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> - the proposals will severely limit ordinary people’s ability to ensure public officials are making lawful, fair and transparent decisions. The legal processes at risk here are ones which guard a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">gainst misuse or abuse of power in everyday life situations such as treatment in nursing homes, hospitals, schools, police stations, health, social care and child protection agencies, and others</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Equal</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> access to justice</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> - the proposals strike at the hear</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t of this principle too, by undermining Legal Aid generally and excluding particular categories of people from the scheme on bases – imprisonment and residence status - that has nothing to do with the strength of the case, its seriousness or their need for</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> advice and representation. This is unfair in principle. It is also unlawful in our view because nothing that approaches an adequate justification for its likely adverse effects has been identified by the Government. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The amounts the Government estimates wi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ll be saved by the proposals on civil Legal Aid appear to be minimal (i.e. “negligible” costs savings through the introduction of the residence eligibility test; £1million for the “no payment without permission” rule; and £1million for the effective ban on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> “test cases” – those with borderline prospects of success). In fact, there are good reasons to think the costs will considerably exceed what will be saved. The key points are set out in a separate submission by Dr Nick Armstrong of Matrix Chambers which w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e have contributed to and endorse. If anything, the evidence of a lack of public confidence in the Legal Aid system is thinner still. Questioned about this driver for the proposals by the Law Society Gazette, the Lord Chancellor commented that he had recei</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ved “lots of letters and emails” which illustrated this problem.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> We do not consider this is an acceptable evidence base for the formulation of Government policy.</span></li></ol></ol><h2 style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Proposal to restrict criminal Legal Aid for prison law matters </span></h2><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to limit criminal legal aid </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">so that prisoners cannot access advice on cases other than those concerning detention and release</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is unrealistic and dangerous in practice and wrong in principle. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The claimed savings are unrealistic </span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">There is currently limited </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">evidence that these proposals will in fact produce the £4 million savings claimed by the government. Instead of seeking expert </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">legal advice and being able to resolve disputes quickly and for the fixed fee of £220, prisoners will have to pursue complaints t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hemselves, which if unsuccessful, could be taken up with the PPO (or by way of judicial review). The consultation states that it costs a prison £35 to deal with a prisoner’s complaint. There is no information as to how much it costs a prison to deal with a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n appeal of a complaint or for the PPO to investigate and respond to a complaint. Inevitably, if prisoners are having to draft and progress complaints themselves, this will increase the time taken to address matters. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The current system of granting prior a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">uthority in treatment cases already sufficiently addresses the concern of unjustified use of public money and funding cases which undermine the credibility of the criminal Legal Aid system. Further, the current system in respect of treatment cases already </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">requires that the prisoner has exhausted the complaints process before seeking legal advice (or that it is not suitable given the circumstances of the case). Therefore, such cases clearly cannot be resolved through recourse to the complaints system. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">onsultation states that since July 2010, only 11 treatment cases have been given prior authority. If this figure is correct, the cost saving in respect of treatment cases will be negligible and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in fact, the proposals might actually increase costs, given t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he burden that will shift to other public authorities’ budgets i.e. the prison service and the PPO.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The alternative options are ineffective </span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The alternative options that will be available to a prisoner, namely use of the internal or Ombudsman’s complaints </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">system, will not be adequate for a number of reasons:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It will be particularly difficult for learning disabled, physically disabled and prisoners with mental health problems to follow the complaints process. In addition, levels of illiteracy are high amongs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t prisoners</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> again, will make it difficult for prisoners to properly engage in the complaints process. Unlike members of the public in the community, prisoners do not have access to informal advice, such as the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Citizen’s Advice Bureau. Although the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">consultation states that NOMS is “committed to comprehensive screening to ensure reasonable adjustments are made for all prisoners with learning disabilities to enable them to use the complaints system”, there is no mention of other categories of vulnerabl</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e prisoner and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> moreover, no details or timetable for this is set out. In any event, the introduction of such measures will incur costs to the public purse. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">There can be significant delays in complaints being dealt with. The prison service aims to deal wi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">th complaints within five days and then appeals within seven days but</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in practice, this rarely happens, due to lack of resources and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in fact, one of the main areas on which the PPO receives complaints is regarding the prison service’s failure to address </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">an internal complaint. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Similarly, the PPO aims to deal with complaints within 12 weeks of receipt</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> but in 2011/12, this only occurred in 53% of cases and the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">average response time was in fact 14 weeks. This is likely to increase if the PPO has to deal wit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">h more complaints and also given that the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> has confirmed that the PPO’s budget is to reduce by 21% between 2010/11 and 2014/15 (as confirmed in the PPO’s annual report for 2011/12).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This delay in addressing matters is likely to be detrimental in a numbe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r of cases, such as in cases concerning transfers to mother and baby units and access to urgent medical treatment for disabled prisoners.  In fact, it demonstrates that the PPO is not a reasonable alternative to obtaining advice and representation from a s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">olicitor. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.04pt; padding-left:2.96pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Certain issues are legally complex and simply cannot be dealt with by way of a complaint. For example, we acted for the interested party in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (on the application of MP) v Secretary of State for Justice and R (on the application of P) v Govern</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">or of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Downview</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Prison </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">[2012] EWHC 214 (Admin</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Prior to commencing judicial review proceedings, the claimant female prisoners had complained to the PPO regarding the lawfulness of the prison’s policy on Childcare Resettlement Leave and the PPO had responded that the policy, and the prison’s decision </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">making, was sound. The High Court found the policy to be unlawful. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">By removing the proposed prison law cases from scope, there is a real risk that there will be an increase in litigation as cases will not be resolved at an early stage as a result of the i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ntervention of specialist targeted legal advice, as is now the case. This may therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> lead to an increased spend in respect of judicial reviews and private law claims. </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This proposal is also wrong in principle for four reasons</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Reduced availability of advice generally </span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Firstly, the removal of funding under the criminal Legal Aid scheme will significantly reduce the number of prisoners receiving legal advice. The consequences of this for prisoners is likely to be that they will no</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t receive legal assistance in the early stages or at all and that there will be a reduction in practitioners (and therefore, choice and availability) with expertise in prison law. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Particular impact on people with mental health problems and learning disab</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ilities</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The consultation recognises that the withdrawal of funding for treatment cases could have an adverse impact on prisoners with mental health issues and/or learning disabilities, given that a significant proportion of funded treatment cases involved </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">such categories of prisoner. Yet these are the very people who are most likely to need help to properly articulate their concerns in a focussed way. There is a linked issue of disabled prisoners under-reporting their disabilities on entry into the prison s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ystem for fear of victimisation by staff or other prisoners. This exacerbates the impact.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">An example of a case which would not have received funding for advice and assistance under the new provisions is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (Gill) v SSJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2010] EWHC 364 Admin in which the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Adm</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">inistrative Court</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> found that the prison had failed to make reasonable adjustments for a learning disabled prisoner in respect of offending behaviour courses and, as a consequence, he was several years past his tariff date. Therefore, the removal of such ca</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ses from scope is indirectly discriminatory and likely to be unlawful unless it can be justified. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Particular impact on women</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The withdrawal of funding will also adversely affect women prisoners in specific categories of treatment cases, namely those conce</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rning mother and baby issues and obtaining temporary release, specifically Childcare Resettlement Leave, which is only available to the primary </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of a child under 16, the majority of whom will be female prisoners. Again, the removal of funding for such</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> cases may be indirectly discriminatory and again, will be unlawful if it cannot be justified. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">No adequate justification</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The impact on prisoners with mental health issues and/or learning disabilities whilst noted is not justified. It is suggested somewhat</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> mutedly that such people can use the internal prison complaints system or Ombudsman scheme to raise their concerns. This bland assertion is not rational. As explained above, authority in many such cases is only granted in circumstances where the person ca</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n establish that they cannot practically do so. The impact on women has simply not been assessed in the Ministry of Justice’s impact assessment. </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Proposed residence test for civil Legal Aid eligibility </span></h2><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> proposes to limit access to all civil Legal A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">id to those with what it characterises as a “strong connection” with the UK – physical presence and past lawful residence. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This proposal is impractical, discriminatory and wholly unjustified.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is worth restating at the outset Lord </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Scarman’s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> summary of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the longstanding principle of equality before the law: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“Every person within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of our laws. There is no distinction between British nationals and others. He who is subject to English law is entitled to its protect</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ion. This principle has been in the law at least since Lord </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Mansfied</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> freed “the black” in Somerset’s Case (1772) 20 St.Tr.1”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">egal Aid eligibility is based on this very principle: it is currently available for all, regardless of their country of residence, provided their case raises an issue in the legal system of England and Wales and comes within the narrow </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">scope of Legal Aid. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This is the ‘connection’ necessary </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and appropriate </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">for eligibility</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">; having a dispute of substance which needs to be resolved in our Courts which cannot otherwise be funded</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. It is fair, sensible and easy to police. It has always been a feature of the Legal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Aid system. </span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A residence test for eligibility for Civil Legal Aid was tentatively proposed in 2008 as part of the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Legal Aid: Refocusing on Priority Cases consultation</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, though it was less onerous (e.g. requiring only proof of address in the UK) and had mor</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e exceptions than what is currently proposed.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> There were strong representations made against it. The proposal was abandoned</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> entirely</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Until now, there have been no indications it was to be resurrected. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Strikingly, at that time the Government was able to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">predict the number of cases likely to be affected, something it has conspicuously failed to do in relation to the current proposals. The estimate was a tiny number: 20 to 40 cases each year. Whatever the number now is, it seems unlikely that it would be si</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">gnificantly higher. That is reinforced by the impact assessment for the current proposals which estimates the savings to be “negligible.”</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The new proposed residence test has four elements. In order to satisfy the test, the person seeking Legal Aid either has to demonstrate to their prospective solicitor’s satisfaction that they: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">are lawfully resident</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in the UK, Crown Dependencies or British</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Overseas Territories at the time the application for civil Legal Aid is made; and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">have been lawfully resident </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">for 12 months, immediately prior to the application for civil Legal Aid, or at any point in the past (either way, the period of residence should </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">be continuous)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> unless they are a baby aged up to one year (in which case lawful presence is sufficient)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">;</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">or</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> they must show that they benefit from an exemption because they are: </span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">serving members of the armed forces and their immediate families; or</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">asylum se</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ekers (including former asylum seekers </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">grated</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> permission to remain).  </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In practice then, the proposed test will prevent</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> both foreign nationals and British nationals applying from outside the UK, Crown Dependencies or British Overseas Territories from recei</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ving civil Legal Aid. It would also have the effect of excluding, for example, visa over</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">stayers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, trafficked persons, clandestine entrants, unaccompanied minors, and failed asylum seekers from receiving civil Legal Aid. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposal was </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">revised on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 5 September </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">with the effect that those who failed the test would remain eligible provided they had </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">particular sorts of case</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">certain detention cases (paragraphs 5, 20, 25, 26 and 27 (and challenges to the lawfulness of detention by way of judicial review under paragraph 19) of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LASPO) – but not all cases challenging past unlawful detention;  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">proceedings b</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rought by recognised victims of trafficking about what immigration status they should be granted and against traffickers and employers (paragraph 32 of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LASPO), victims of domestic violence and forced marriage (paragraphs 11, 12, 13,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 16, 28 and 29 of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LASPO)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">certain protection of children cases (paragraphs 1, 349, 950, 10, 15 and 23 of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LASPO); and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">pecial Immigration Appeals Commission cases (paragraph 24 of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LAS</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">PO). </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is important to note that there are no general concessions for ‘vulnerable’ people, those who have been ‘trafficked’, or children. Only particular sorts of case have been exempted. So, for example:   </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">cases brought to challenge ongoing unlawful de</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">tention will be exempt from the residence test, but those about past unlawful detention will be subject to it; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">proceedings brought to establish that a person is a victim of trafficking, or to challenge failures to investigate or prosecute, or to adequatel</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y support them during a prosecution will be fully subject to the residence test and many </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">trafficking victims will fail it;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">many family cases are now included</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in the exemptions</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, but not child abduction ones with an international element which wi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ll inevitably involve parties who fail the residence test; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">cases about whether children should be in care will be covered, but cases about the adequacy of the support they receive once in care, or when they leave it, will be subject to the residence te</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">st</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and many children will fail it.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Despite the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">limited</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">inconsistent</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> concessions</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, the proposal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">remains</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> unworkable in practice to the point of being dangerous and wrong in principle. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">An unworkable test </span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">First, w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hat is proposed is very far from a “common sense” test. In practice, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">every</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> applicant for civil Legal Aid will need to satisfy it by producing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">original, documentary </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">evidence of past lawful residence. Neither the time nor the costs involved have been estimat</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is no overstatement to say the implications of this for provision of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ivil Legal Aid are phenomenal. In 2012-13 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">alone</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">there were</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">590</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">410 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ivil </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Help </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">funded acts of assistance; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">139,083 authorised acts of certificated representation.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">this one year alone, each of these </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">729,483 acts of assistance </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would have needed to be preceded by a residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> administered by solicitors and audited by the Legal Aid Agency</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Strikingly</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> these statistics do not feature in the proposals at all. The scal</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e of the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">practical </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">problems the test will create is, apparently, considered to be irrelevan</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> by the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Nor is there any</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> indication in the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">original </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">consultation paper</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> or the 5 September Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps document</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of what will be involved</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in checking current and pas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t lawful residence. It is clear, however, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">that this h</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">as been given no real thought. A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">original consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">paper notes: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The specific </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> requirements have not yet been decided upon. However, individuals who do not already have evidence of UK nationality may have to pay a fee for a copy of their birth certificate or other documentation if they do not have easy access to them. Claimants may </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">also experience a delay in their cases whilst documentation is sought.” </span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In practice however, any ‘lawful residence’ test will involve verifying past immigration status (to establish legality of residence) and physical presence for a purpose that can be de</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">scribed as ‘residence’. In law, there is no single concept of residence, however. Residence may be ‘ordinary’, temporary (for some fixed, finite purpose) or open</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ended but not settled.  Further details of the difficulties in establishing residence and immi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">gration status are given in the ILPA </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">submission</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which we endorse. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This firm, unlike many that will be affected, has an experience immigration law department the expertise of which we could draw upon. Yet i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n our experience, i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t may take days or weeks in pra</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ctice to gather adequate evidence of past, lawful residence. In the meantime</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> urgent legal action may well need to be taken. The consultation offers no answer to what should be done while this acknowledged delay is occurring. Nor is it clear what will happ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">en if past residence status simply cannot be verified. In some case</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s -</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for example those involving children, homeless people or trafficking victims</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> adequate evidence will simply not be available.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In others, solicitors may lack sufficient knowledge of the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> complexities of immigration law to make a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">decision.  It is unclear what additional support, and how any would be paid for, will be provided by the Government to fill this gap.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Family cases are one obvious example of the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">unworkability</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of the test</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and accou</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">nt for most Legal Helps and Legal Aid Certificates</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. They involve urgency, high stakes, and many people who may not pass the residence test, or be able to demonstrate that they do quickly</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><h1 style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Section 10 will not mitigate the problems the residence test will cr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">eate </span></h1><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Paragraph</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 3.54 of the Consultation Paper suggests that section 10 LASPO exceptional funding can be granted to fund cases excluded from the scope of the normal Legal Aid scheme. The suggestion here appears to be that exceptional funding can therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">somehow mitigate the effects of the residence test. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">We do not </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">agree. Our view is that s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ection 10 funding will not be available to people who are disqualified from eligibility altogether. It only empowers the Lord Chancellor to grant funding for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">cases</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> that are out of scope</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and the Government has yet to explain why it has reached a different view</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is also clear that exceptional funding is a near theoretical safe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y net because of the practical difficulties in obtaining it. To date</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> less than 2 per ce</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">nt of applications for such funding made have been successful - hardly a practical and effective means of ensuring compliance with Article 6 ECHR.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Even </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">if it were</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> available, funding of this kind </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would only provide</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for the most limited assistance in a limit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed range of case</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">: those where there is an ECHR or EU </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">right</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to publicly funded representation. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">That is the stated scope of the scheme. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">There is considerable room for debate about which </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">cases fall within the scope of such rights and, where funding is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">necessary, what precisely is needed. In practice</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> that debate will inevitably result in litigation. That will be on a case by case basis because the extent to which representation is necessary will depend on the nature of the case and the circumstances of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the person seeking funding. The proposal will positively undermine cost savings and efficiency by creating the need for complex decision and associated litigation where, at present, there is none.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The residence test in practice: </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">international </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">family cases  </span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In any</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> family</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> case with an international dimension, it is likely that at least one party will not meet the residence test.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The effects of removing all eligibility for Legal Aid for some of the parties to such disputes while leaving others wh</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">olly within the scheme do not appear to have been grappled with at all. They are likely to have significant costs implications for the family courts. Indeed the knock-on effects in costs terms for the parties that will remain legally aided will far exceed </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the savings. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The Government has been warned about such effects by the senior judiciary in the recent past. In </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Wright v Michael Wright Supplies Ltd </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">[2013] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 234, Lord Justice Ward stated, at [2]: </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“What I find so depressing is that the case highlig</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hts the difficulties increasingly encountered by the judiciary at all levels when dealing with </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">litigants in person. Two problems in particular are revealed. The first is how to bring order to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> chaos which litigants in person invariably – and wholly unde</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rstandably – manage to create in putting forward their claims and defences. Judges should not have to micro-manage cases, coaxing and cajoling the parties to focus on the issues that need to be resolved. Judge Thornton did a brilliant job in that regard ye</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t, as this case shows, that can be disproportionately time-consuming. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">It may be saving the Legal Services Commission which no longer offers Legal Aid for this kind of litigation but saving expenditure in one public department in this instance simply increa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ses it in the courts. The expense of three judges of the Court of Appeal dealing with this kind of appeal is enormous. The consequences by way of delay of other appeals which need to be heard are unquantifiable. The appeal would certainly never have occurr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ed if the litigants had been represented.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">With more and more self-represented litigants, this problem is not going to go away. We may have to accept that we live in austere times, but as I come to the end of eighteen years service in this court, I shall no</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t refrain from expressing my conviction that justice will be ill served indeed by this emasculation of Legal Aid” (emphasis added)</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 25.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Although the consultation and response from the government states that they “</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would ensure that legal aid would continue to be</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> available where necessary to comply with [their] obligations under EU or international law set out in Schedule 1 to LASPO,” the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps document </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">does </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">include</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> proceedings under paragraph 17 of Schedule 1 to LASPO as exempt from the residence test though other paragraphs are specifically and clearly exempted.  Making legal aid “available” mean</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> that any applicant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">who</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> does not meet the residence test wishing to m</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ake an application under EU and international agreements regarding children w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ill </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">be required to apply for exceptional funding.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">However, there is no guarantee that exceptional funding will be granted and the cost of preparation of an application for except</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ional funding itself is likely to be prohibitive, for example the need for translation of supporting documents. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The introduction of a residence test will not prevent international parental child abduction; it will simply disadvantage parents who require a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> remedy, which will in turn adversely affect the children involved.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">At best, even if parents are able to obtain exceptional funding to make applications for the return of abducted children there would be a severe delay following the child’s abduction, leav</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ing children vulnerable and separated unilaterally from one of their parents, potentially their primary </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, and away from their homes.  This flies in the face of the obligations for children to be summarily and speedily returned to the country where the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y are habitually resident.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> In addition to the potential harm and distress that could be caused to individual children, broadly the cessation of legal aid for child abduction would allow parents to openly thwart court orders made in other countries regar</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ding a child’s welfare and leave the left behind parent with no remedy due to the cost of proceedings, even as a litigant in person due to the court application fees and costs of travel to England for court hearings.  Considering the ethos of respect for o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ther countries’ jurisdiction regarding children that is behind both the Hague Convention on Child Abduction 1980 and the Hague Convention of the Protection of Children 1996, to which the UK is a signatory, it would be highly detrimental to international ju</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">dicial relations were these remedies to become prohibitively expensive or difficult </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to obtain.   To put it bluntly, why would other countries respect the UK jurisdiction when the UK allows their orders to be disregarded by a prohibitive system for making a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n application </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">for remedy?</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The following is an illustrative yet non-exhaustive list of the cases we have handled for people who would fail the residence test and so be denied Legal Aid if the proposals are implemented. It is impossible to understand how t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he Government has concluded that these cases concern people with an ‘insufficient connection’ to merit them being represented or that application of such a test represents “common sense”.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Father of an abducted child</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. We represented the father in child abd</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">uction proceedings.  The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">child lived with her </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">father in Latvia </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and he was her primary </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">carer</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.  The mother lived in the UK.  There had been agreement that the child would visit the mother in the UK for a holiday, but the mother retained the child in the UK </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">after the end of the holiday and refused to return the child to the father’s care. The application was made under the Hague Convention on Child Abduction 1980</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, the purpose of which is to ensure that children are returned swiftly to the country where they a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">re habitually resident when abducted</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.  Our commitment to the Hague Convention provides the left behind parent with public funding to bring an application for the return of their child. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The father did not speak English and did not have funds to attend court</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in England.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposed residence test would mean that the father would not have been entitled to public funding and would therefore have been unable to afford </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">representation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in court proceedings for the return</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> his child to their home in which the ch</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ild had been settled and happy for some time. In this case, we were able to agree a voluntary return of the child with the mother and the case was concluded within the 6 week timeframe expected of Hague Convention cases.  This resulted in reduc</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> legal cos</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ts all around and sav</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the valuable time of the court</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> by removing the need for</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a final contested hearing. Had the father not been able to instruct specialist child abduction lawyers with public funding, he</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> may not have been able to bring his application a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t all due to lack of funds to attend court or lack of language skills to make representations to court </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">as a litigant in person,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and if he did do so </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> have ultimately taken up much more court time.  It would have been highly unlikely that the partie</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s would have been able to reach an agreement so swiftly, which would have </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">meant</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a much higher cost to the state in terms of court time and services</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> at best.  At worst, the country’s obligations under the Hague Convention on Child Abduction 1980</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Council Regulation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(EC) No 2201/2003</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">(Brussels II Revised) as this was a European country, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would be left unmet as the father would be unable to afford to apply in person at all or be unable to represent himself due to language barriers</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Father </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">of an abducted child</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. We represented a father in Hague Convention proceedings on his application for the summary return of his six year old son to the U</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">SA</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. The proceedings have an exceptionally complicated factual background which involves extensive litiga</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">tion both in England and in the USA which has been </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">going</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> since 2008. In March 2010</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the US court dealt with the final </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hearing of the parties’ divorce and custody proceedings and made the equivalent of a residence order in the father’s favour. The court </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">made a number of adverse findings against the mother including that she was an abduction risk to the child. Following the hearing, the child resided with the father and the mother resided in England.  The mother sought unsuccessfully to appeal the order. T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he mother then made an application to a different court alleging that the child was habitually resident in England and that the father’s retention of the child pursuant to the US order was a wrongful retention for the purposes of the Hague Convention. In A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ugust 2011</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the mother’s application prevailed and an order was made requiring the father to deliver up the child to the mother and for the child to be returned to England. The father complied with the order and the mother duly returned to England with the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> child.  The father lodged an appeal against the Hague Convention decision in the USA and the appeal was determined in his favour in July 2012.  In August 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> an order was made requiring the mother to return the child to the father in the USA.  The mothe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r did not return the child so the father issued Hague Convention proceedings in this jurisdiction. We act for the father. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposed residence test would mean that the father would not have been entitled to public funding and would therefore have been un</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">able to afford to be represented in court proceedings for the return his child to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the USA. The legal issues in this case are novel and have never been considered by the English Court. Faced with complex</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and novel</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> legal arguments regarding the operation of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the Hague Convention, the father could not have represented himself effectively. Conversely, the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">proposed residence test would mean that the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> mother would still have been entitled to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">public funding and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> indeed she has been represented by Queens Counsel throu</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ghout the proceedings. The proposed residence test would create an inequality of arms in these types of international cases which cannot be fair of just (especially in light of the mother’s wrongdoing). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Abandoned spouses</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> and victims of forced marriage</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ese are (usually) women who are taken abroad under a false pretence and stranded there without their travel documents, whilst their child remains in England.  These women require legal aid to bring applications in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Wardship</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to be reunited with their childre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n. They would not be able to secure legal aid to do so after the introduction of the proposed residence test.  Even if they had been resident in the UK for the requisite 12 month period, their lack of presence in the jurisdiction means they would not be el</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">igible.  Victims of forced marriage may have been brought to this country, or taken abroad, under duress.  They will either not be eligible for legal aid because they are not in the UK, or would have severe difficulties in proving they had been resident fo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r the requisite period.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Parents in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">cases under Brussels II Revised relating to child protection</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">We represent the father in care proceedings </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> heard as an urgent measure for the protection of the child under Article 20 of Brussels II Revised </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The mother </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and child were living in Sweden. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The current proceedings commenced in September 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, whilst the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mother and child were on holiday in this jurisdiction, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">when the child was placed in foster care in this jurisdiction pursuant to a Police Protection Order beca</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">use of concerns in respect of the mother’s mental health, care of the child and flight risk following a number of admissions to different hospitals in England in recent weeks.  The local authority commenced care proceedings and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he mother contested the jur</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">isdiction of English court to make orders in respect of the child. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> client made an application pursuant to Article 15 of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Brussels II Revised</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for a request to Sweden for jurisdiction in respect of the child to be transferred to the English Court.  The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">High Court decided to make </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> request to Sweden </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">but the Swedish Court rejected the request as it deemed there were no live proceedings in Sweden to transfer and further held that Article 15 of ‘Brussels II Revised’ relates to a transfer of live proceeding</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s and not subject matter jurisdiction. There was a contested hearing at which the English High Court held that it had jurisdiction to hear the care proceedings in this matter. T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he High Court was satisfied that the child is at risk of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">suffering </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">harm and tha</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t the interim care order should continue pending further assessments.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> The mother has been granted leave to appeal the decision and a hearing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is listed </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in the Court of Appeal at the end of October</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. Given the complex legal arguments in this case, all pa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rties are represented by leading and junior counsel. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Requests pursuant to Article 15 of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Brussels II Revised</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> are rare and, as far as we are aware, there are no reported authorities in this jurisdiction.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t is possible that there will be an ap</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">plication to the Court of Appeal for a reference to be made to the Court of Justice of the European Union to determine whether </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Article 15 of ‘Brussels II Revised’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> relates to a transfer of live proceedings and/or subject matter jurisdiction. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposed re</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sidence test would mean that the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ther would not have been entitled to public funding and would therefore have been unable to afford to be represented in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">court proceedings</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> although her child had been removed from her care by the State</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. The legal iss</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ues in this case are novel and have never been considered by the English Court</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s, and indeed may need to be considered by the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Court of Justice of the European Union. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Although she is not our client, f</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">aced with </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">complex and novel legal arguments, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and due </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to the fact that she suffers from mental health problems, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ther could not have represented h</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">self effectively</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in these proceedings</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. She would have had to act as litigant in person against three parties that are represented by leading and junior couns</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">el due to the complex nature of this case. Furthermore, where the State seeks to intervene in people’s lives by removing their children from their care</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which is an available remedy under Article 20 of Brussels II Revised</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, it is only </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">fair </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and proper that th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ere is an equality of arms and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">those such individuals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> (many of whom are vulnerable and have mental health problems) should be properly represented by lawyers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">other wise</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> there is arguably </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">an interference with their Article 8 right</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to family life.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The residence test in practice: victims of crime, abuse and wrongdoing </span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The practical </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">problems</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> associated with the residence test will not just be experienced by those whose connection to the UK is a close family one. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Another significant category of people are those whose connection arises from a serious wrong done to them in the UK, or by its repr</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">esentatives in its name. These people are victims, often of very serious crimes. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The Government very recently consulted upon and restated its policy on ‘Helping and Supporting Victims of Crime’</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. It recognised that: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“proper protection and support for vic</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">tims of crime is a fundamental part of a civilised justice system. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and committed itself to “action” to “ensure that victims get the support they need to cope with the aftermath”. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">But, despite improvements over the last two decades, the system has continu</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed to fall short in helping victims recover from crime, supporting them through the stresses of investigation and trial, and providing the right support at the right time.</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Such</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> words will ring hollow for those who cannot satisfy the residence test: </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Aid will be denied to the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">victims of the most extreme wrongdoing abroad by British authorities</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> within territory that they have taken responsibility for. One example handle</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> by this firm is the ongoing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Batang</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Kali massacre case, </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Keyu</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">) </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">v</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Foreign Secretary</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and </span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Secretary of State</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> for Defence</span><span style="color:#444444; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2012] EWHC 2445 (Admin) (DC).</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, a challenge to the UK’s failure to take responsibility for, and properly inquire into, the killing of 24 unarmed civilians in colonial Malaya in 1948 despite several of the soldiers involv</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed confessing to murder. Others include cases about inadequate investigation of killings and torture in Iraq (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (Ali </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Zaki</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Mousa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">) v Secretary of State for Defence No.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">[2013] EWHC 1412 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Al-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sweady</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> &amp; Ors, v Secretary of State for the Defence </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">[2009] EWHC 1687 (Admin) and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Al-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sweady</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> &amp; Ors, v Secretary of State for the Defence </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">[2009] EWHC 2387 (Admin)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">) and into British complicity in torture (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (Mohammed) v Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2008] EWCA 2519). </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">One obvious gro</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">up are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">victims of criminal trafficking or forced labour</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, who will generally not have the necessary length and legality of residence to access justice. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">For example, we acted for Y who had been trafficked into the UK from a rural Tanzanian village and subjec</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t to forced labour, raped by the father and abused by the mother who brought her into the UK on a false passport less than a year beforehand. She had no lawful immigration status. When she escaped she tried to get help from the police, who told her to retu</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rn to the family. Shortly after, she managed to run away again. After being homeless for a few weeks, a charity eventually referred her to us. We were instructed a few days before the deadline for any judicial review of the police decision to close her cas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e without investigating what had happened to her. They also reported that due </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to the language barrier her account was unclear, an approach which in itself amounted to indirect race discrimination. Following a detailed letter before action on Full Represent</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ation Legal Aid (due to the urgency) the police and CPS agreed to investigate, sent a team to Tanzania, and prosecuted the offences testing new anti-trafficking powers given to the police. Under the proposals, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">even with the concessions made in the Transfor</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ming Legal Aid: Next Steps  document, Y </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">would not have passed the residence test, nor would we have been paid, as the case settled pre-permission.  </span></li><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A recognition of the importance of access to Legal Aid for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">victims of domestic violence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> was recognised unde</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r LASPO but the proposed residence will take out of scope many victims who would otherwise be eligible. For example, we acted for FC, a Bolivian national, who was an </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">overstayer</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> in the UK. She lived with her husband and two young children aged 2 and 4. FC w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">as subjected to serious physical and sexual domestic violence from her husband. She was assaulted and repeatedly raped by him in front of their two sons. FC tried on many occasions to flee the family home but was repeatedly refused assistance by the local </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">authority. She always had to return to the family home and face further violence as she had no recourse to public funds. She sought advice from a local charity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> wh</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ich</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> put her in touch with </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Bindmans</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. The local authority finally agreed to assist FC and her t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">wo sons under of the Children Act following receipt of a letter before action.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> This case would fail the residence test because community care cases of this kind are not subject to any exemption. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Family members of people killed here</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> will not be entitled to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> support. The family of Jean Charles de </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Menezes</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> would be denied Legal Aid, for example, as would that of the two French students stabbed to death in London in 2008. Further examples of such cases can be found in the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Transforming Legal Aid </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">consultation resp</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">onse of INQUEST which we have seen and endorse. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The residence test in practice: other civil cases  </span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">many</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> other plainly deserving cases where the proposed test will not be met. Examples include: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Children who have come to the UK with family and w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">hose family relationships break down</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and who require resolution of their immigration status in their own rights.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> For example, our former client Mr S was brought to the UK from Angola by his father. He was subsequently physically and psychologically abused </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">by his father and step-mother. He ran away from home at 13 and ended up living on the streets for several months, where he was sexually abused by a strange</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. He eventually came to the attention of the local authority, who instructed </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Bindmans</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to resolve his immigration position. He was found to have no status at all. Under these proposals, he would have had no recourse to assistance. We ultimately obtained ind</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">efinite leave to remain on his behalf. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unaccompanied minors</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> with no status and urgent need for community care support and accommodation from a local authority </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">pursuant to complex ‘Looked After Children’ rules </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">are frequently flouted by Social Services</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. We handle many such cases, for example that of Ms K who was brought from Sierra Leone to the UK when she was 16. Subsequently, she escaped an abusive domestic situation in which she had been forced to work as a prostitute. She ended up destitute. We were</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> instructed to urgently challenge the local authority’s refusal to accommodate and support her under the Looked After Children statutory regime. Support was provided following a detailed pre-action letter. She had no status or documents, and would have bee</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n left destitute under the proposals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> as cases of this kind are fully subject to the residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Children who have been </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">granted a short period of discretionary leave to remain</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> despite being refused asylum. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">At 13, another former client’s mother arrang</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ed for him to be brought into the UK for his own safety following the execution of his father in Afghanistan. His asylum application was refused and he was granted just 6 months’ leave to remain. This meant he was deprived of the right of appeal against th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e asylum decision. He therefore needed urgent immigration advice.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">People who are lawfully in the UK but whose circumstances change within a year</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> so they need to make a different/new immigration status application</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for example, people whose relationships </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">break down because of domestic violence.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> One such case was that of a former client, Mrs R</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, who</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> was an </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ndian national, living in the UK with her husband, on a spousal visa. She had no recourse to public funds and two children under the age of 4, both of wh</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">om were British. Her husband was sexually, physically and emotionally abusive towards her in front of the children. Her eldest child was displaying symptoms of trauma from having witnessed the violence. Following a particularly violent episode, Mrs R fled </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the family home and sought temporary accommodation from the local authority but was refused. She had no money for food for the children and had fled the house without any belongings. She feared for her and the children's safety on return. She sought advice</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> from a local woman's group which managed to accommodate her and the children for one night. We sent a letter before claim to the local authority and they maintained their decision. We issued a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">judicial review</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and an interim injunction was granted, requiri</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ng the local authority to support the family pursuant to their statutory duties. One week later, they backed down and provided accommodation and support to the family in a place of safety. As she was no longer with her abusive spouse, unless had applied fo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r further leave under different complex rules, her immigration status would have been at risk. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.04pt; padding-left:2.96pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Visitors / short term students</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. For example, we advised students at London Met University who moved to the UK to start their degrees only to find the university</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> had summarily lost its licence to educate overseas students. They would not have had access to advice on the options in the complex area of student visas, fees, and education under these proposals. The licence was restored following a judicial review of t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he withdrawal decision. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Long term </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">overstayers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> with strong family/private life</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> rights cases. For example, our client Ms A was a Jamaican national who had lived in the UK for over 10 years but would not have passed the lawful residence test. She had made an</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> application for leave to remain for herself and her 6 year old son. A decision was awaited from the Home Office and she had no recourse to public funds. Her husband, a British national was violent and had raped her on several occasions. She sought assista</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">nce from the local authority so she and her son could flee the violence. She was advised that it was not necessary to provide support as she could lock herself and her son in the living room to protect themselves. We sent a letter before claim, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">which did n</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ot result in a satisfactory outcome. We prepared an application for judicial review and on the day of preparing to issue the claim, the local authority settled the case and accommodated our client.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.56pt; padding-left:3.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Families whose loved ones have died in immigration detent</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ion or when being removed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.05pt; padding-left:2.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">British residents or citizens overseas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, including those who have been extraordinarily rendered, even if on the basis of mistaken identity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Discrimination </span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">These practical consequences also demonstrate that the proposed residence test is wrong in principle. The reason is that this proposal is discriminatory, and cannot begin to be justified on the basis suggested by the Government. It is therefore unlawful. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In the case of trafficking victims (see above for examples) there is a straightforward and absolute EU law prohibition on discrimination of the kind the proposal envisages. Under Article 12(2) of the Trafficking Directive 2011/36 EU,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> member states shall en</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sure that victims of trafficking in human beings have access without delay to legal advice, and, in accordance with the role of victims in the relevant justice </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">system, to legal representation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. In addition, under Article 15(2) of the EU Convention on Anti-t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rafficking 2005 the UK shall provide for legal redress, and give victims the right to free legal advice and representation assistance on remedies. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Application of the residence test is recognised in the consultation paper itself as having a particular adve</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rse impact on others who are not nationals of the UK or its territories (it will have very similar effects on those who have non-UK national and ethnic origins). There are legal prohibitions on measures that have this kind of discriminatory impact unless i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t can be justified. Again, these are not acknowledged in the consultation paper. They include: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Article 6 of the ECHR read with Article 14</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.  Save in exceptional cases, it will be difficult to show that failure to grant Legal Aid amounts to a violation of A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rticle 6 (the fair trial provision) by denying the individual access to a court.  However, Article 14 requires that there should be no unjustified difference of treatment, between people who are similarly placed, in relation to the enjoyment of the rights </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">guaranteed by the Convention.  This broadens the argument, meaning that if a particular facility (such as </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid) falls within the “ambit” of a Convention right, a state may not discriminate against one class of person by comparison with another.  Since</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Legal Aid is available only for matters of domestic law for proceedings before the domestic courts, it is hard to see how their place of residence – and indeed the lawful or unlawful character of their residence – can be a basis for distinguishing between</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> them.  They are all, by definition, subject to the jurisdiction of the UK courts.  Article 1 of the Convention requires states to secure the Convention rights to “everyone within their jurisdiction”. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Section 29 of the Equality Act</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. This prohibits discrim</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ination (including indirect discrimination) in relation to the provision of services, including the services of public authorities.  It should be noted that section 2(5)(b) of LASPO empowers the Lord Chancellor to make different provision for different cla</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sses of person but the Equality Act, however, does not contain – as the Race Relations Act 1976 contained – a general provision excluding acts done pursuant to a statutory requirement.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">EU law</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.  Various provisions of EU law may prohibit unjustified discri</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mination. There is a general prohibition on nationality discrimination within the ambit of the EU treaty. Provisions on equal treatment of free moving citizens prohibit discrimination in relation to social advantages.  Article 47 of the EU Charter of Funda</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mental Rights provides that Legal Aid shall be made available to those who lack sufficient resources to ensure effective access to justice in relation to the implementation of EU law.  However, its scope is the same as Article 6 of the ECHR.  The Charter a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">lso contains a non-discrimination provision.  A requirement of residence within a Member State will fall foul of the EU equality provision – most residence requirements are therefore EU-wide rather than linked to the territory of one state.  Council Direct</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ive 2002/8/EC provides that persons involved in cross-border disputes are entitled to appropriate Legal Aid to ensure their effective access to justice</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> – a category expressly provided for under </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">44 of Schedule 1 of LASPO, but fully subject to the resid</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ence test</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.  Article 4 of the Directive also provides that Member States must grant Legal Aid without discrimination to Union citizens and third-country nationals residing lawfully in a Member State.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">The common law principle of equal treatment, combined w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ith the common law right of access to the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> prohibits the Lord Chancellor from making unjustified distinctions that undermine principle of equal treatment in relation to a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> fundamental common law right. </span></li></ol><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">These obligations are echoed in international la</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">w. For example: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">UN Basic Principles on the Role of Lawyers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> at paragraph 2 require Governments to “ensure that efficient procedures and responsive mechanisms for effective and equal access to lawyers are provided for all persons within their territory </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and subject to their jurisdiction, without distinction of any kind, such as discrimination </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">based on race, colour, ethnic origin, sex, language, religion, political or other opinion, national or social origin, property, birth, economic or other status.” The</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 2005 Basic Principles and Guidelines on the Right to a Remedy and Reparation for Victims of Gross Violations of International Human Rights Law and Serious Violations of International Humanitarian Law have similar provisions. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">International Convention </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">has a similar provision at Articles 2 and 26; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Equality conventions such as the UN Convention on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">obliges the Government to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“guarantee the right of everyone, without distinction </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">as to …  national or ethnic origin, to equality before the law, notably in the enjoyment of the following rights: (a) The right to equal treatment before the tribunals and all other organs administering justice” (Article 5); and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">UNCRC</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> requires children</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">’s interests to be protected in legal proceedings and for their voices to be heard. These rights must be guaranteed without discrimination.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.04pt; padding-left:2.96pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The UN </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> has a similar provision at Article 2</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which requires access to justice and effective enjoyment of rights on non-discriminatory grounds.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Absence of justification </span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> seek to justify the discrimination as being a proportionate means of achieving a legitimate aim – the test will be broadly </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">similar under all the provisions identified above.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he justification </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">offered </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">for discrimination </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in the original </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">consultation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is not cost: the cost savings are considered “negligible”. Instead, t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he rationale is twofold: first, the need for a UK  ‘connection</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">’: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“3.42 We are concerned that individuals with little or no connection to this </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">country are currently able to claim Legal Aid to bring civil legal actions at UK taxpayers’ expense. These may be people who have never set foot in England or Wales, or those </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">who have never paid taxes in the UK, but who are yet able to benefit financially from the civil Legal Aid scheme. Alternatively these may be people who are in the country but whose connection is tenuous because they are simply here on a visa as visitors, o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r because they have temporary admission. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">3.43 We need to introduce a common sense test to address this anomalous situation, which we believe is currently unfair to the UK taxpayer. We believe that limited public funds for civil Legal Aid should be targete</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">d at those who have a strong connection to the UK.”</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and secondly to deter ‘forum shopping’: </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">“3.44 We are also concerned that the availability of Legal Aid for cases brought in this country, irrespective of the person’s connection with this country, may encourage people to bring disputes here.”  </span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e latter</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> appears to have been dropped as a justif</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ication in the 5 September documents. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Even were </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">either</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> concern based on credible evidence rather than the “letters and e mails” the Lord Chancellor has apparently received, they would not amount to a legitimate aim.  As explained above, what those who wil</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">l be excluded have in common is that they all have cases to bring or defend before the UK courts, and they already have to meet strict merits tests.  That is their ‘connection’ with the UK.  In many cases, the connection will be involuntary, such as the fa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mily and victim cases listed above. To suggest that such people should be denied equal access to the Courts because they have failed to form a sufficient ‘connection’ with, or make a sufficient contribution to, the UK is absurd. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The section 10 LASPO schem</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e is no answer for the reasons we have given above. But also, the very fact of having to make an exceptional funding application, with different criteria and limited rights of review, in itself makes it substantially more difficult for the individual to ge</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t Legal Aid.  Imposition of these additional obstacles may in themselves constitute unlawful discrimination, when they are not imposed on UK residents.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Proportionality </span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Even were the aim legitimate, the Government would face yet further problems in justify</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ing the test as a proportionate means of bringing it about.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The first is that it has not assessed impact at all despite its obligation to do so under section 149 Equality Act 2010. Given the tiny number of cases said to be involved (estimated at 20-40 per </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">annum in the 2008 consultation), it might have been thought easy to undertake proper research into them to see which would be left entirely outside the scheme if the proposals are implemented and, perhaps more importantly still, what the impact would be on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> those affected. e.g. the extent to which the ‘credibility’ of the scheme is undermined by Legal Aid being granted to non-residents rather depends on what the Legal Aid is used for; people may feel that it is not legitimate for Legal Aid to be used to spon</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sor forum shopping (which is suggested at paragraph 3.44), but that cases exposing alleged human rights abuses by British authorities or other serious wrongdoing ought to be supported. There is simply no analysis of what these cases are, and so the real im</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">pact is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">unquantified</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The second difficulty for the Government is that the Courts – both domestic and international – have been extremely sceptical about measures which discriminate indirectly on national origins grounds. Very compelling justification is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">required, as this is a form of racial discrimination, and therefore inherently ‘suspect’. For examples, see </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Gaygasuz</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> v. Austria</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> (1996) EHRR 364, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Elias v Ministry of Defence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">[2006] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 1293 and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Anakoma</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Yula</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> v Belgium</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Appn</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. 45413/07,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">10 March 2009. </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Proposal to end funding for pre-permission judicial review work </span></h2><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A helpful concession has been made on pre permission work for claims that are not issued. We understand the Government’s position is that this work will remain remunerated by the Legal Aid Au</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">thority, as now. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">However, i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">still </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">proposed that solicitors and barristers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> should only be paid for work carried out on an </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">issued </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">claim</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> for judicial </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">review for</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> judicial review, including a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ny</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">permission</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> hearing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">if perm</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ission is granted by the Court. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid Authority will have discretion to fund cases resolved before a judge decides on permission to proceed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">his will be exercised retrospectively. A further mini-consultation has been launched focusing on criteria that the Legal Aid Authority will u</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">se. But this concession is hollow whatever its outcome because the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> still expects claimant firms to take all pre-action steps (including any mediation)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to issue and pursue complex cases without any funding in place. The proposed discretion to grant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">it only once a case is concluded leaves all the risks and linked disincentives intact.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Once again, this proposal is unworkable, dangerous and wrong in principle.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The ‘civil Legal Aid credibility assessment’ underpinning the consultation concludes that th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e costs </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">caused</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> by the proposed change to the state will be negligible. ‘LAA Administration: may experience a small one-off increase in administration costs to cover any amendments to financial systems and training.’ We consider this is utterly wrong for th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e reasons below. It also estimates that there will be a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">saving</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of just £1m. This appears to be based on there being costs savings associated with 800 cases which do not receive permission: see paragraph 31 of the Credibility Impact Analysis. Needless to sa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y, these costs are relatively insignificant when compared to the Legal Aid budget overall. So the justification for the proposals in cost / benefit terms would need to be compelling. As discussed below, it is not. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The other justification offered for these</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> proposals is to ‘restore public confidence’ which has apparently been dented by a perception that weak cases are being taken to permission which should never have been funded in the first place. This overlooks the very thorough filter system which is alre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ady in place when applications for Full Representation are made. Significantly, as of April 2013, that system is operated exclusively by the LAA, practitioners having had their devolved powers to grant themselves Legal Aid removed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Incomplete data and flawed assumptions </span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposals are not based on adequate data and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">assumptions about how judicial review operates in practice are not accurate. This deficiency manifests itself in a number of ways</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It is said that 845 of the 179</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">9 Legal Aid cases in which permission was sought ended after permission was refused.  There is no analysis of the reasons why permission was refused, and although in 330 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">cases providers recorded that the case was of substantive benefit, this is not regarde</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">d as sufficient justification to retain funding. We do not consider this data is accurate; certainly it is not helpful. It does not reflect our own experience which is that a high proportion of issued cases end up settling, though not necessarily with cost</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s being agreed to or awarded. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">That such cases should not be remunerated when there is a positive benefit is quite wrong. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Varda</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Bondy</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and Maurice </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Sunkin</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of the Public Law Project’s pre-publication draft states that “there can be no doubt that the statistics</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> cited by the Lord Chancellor present a grossly under-estimated success rate of judicial review challenges”. Further, the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> statistics “provide at best an unreliable evidence base for reform; at worst they are grossly misleading”. We agree. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">At paragra</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ph 41</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of the original consultation paper</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, it is noted that “[t]he assumed cost of preparing a permission application is uncertain.” This is worrying given the assumption made in the Annex K Equality Impact Assessment that the sustainability of the Legal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Aid market is unlikely to be adversely affected. Without knowing how much providers will lose, and how much financial risks they are being asked to shoulder</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> such a conclusion cannot be reached. In fact, in many cases the pre permission costs are higher th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">an the figure estimated because the case is complex and requires significant amounts of evidence to be gathered or considered, or because attempts to settle or narrow the dispute are being made, for example through mediation. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A further fundamental flaw is</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">original </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">consultation paper’s assumption that the mere fact of not getting permission means that the claim should never have been brought. That is false for at least four reasons. First, a case which is strong on its face when issued may emerge as wea</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">k once the defendant public body explains its position; that may well happen in the acknowledgement of service only after the claim is filed, despite the pre-action protocol requirements on defendants. Secondly, circumstances may change once proceedings ar</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e underway, making what was a strong claim academic. Costs are not awarded in these cases, yet they have been properly brought and the work should be funded. Thirdly, the rates of grant of permission on similar cases vary hugely from judge to judge. Again,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> we refer to the Public Law Project’s research on this issue. Fourth, the right of renewing a permission application exists because it is accepted that High Court judges sometimes get it wrong, and there is value in oral argument about the issues. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Two exam</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ples may help. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The first is non-legally aided</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> case. Permission was refused by </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Mitting</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> J to a number of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">our clients</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> seeking to challenge the Metropolitan Police’s refusal to confirm whether or not they were </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">victims of phone hacking</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. The judge considered th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">at the evidence of widespread hacking that might include their phones was slight and that the police were not obliged to inform victims of crime that they were, in fact, victims. The application for permission was renewed at a hearing and was granted. The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Metropolitan Police then conceded the claim in full and released the information they held </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">about widespread hacking to the victims of this crime, including the claimants. Yet from the consultation paper’s perspective, this would be a ‘weak case’ that ‘neve</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">r should have been brought’. The consultation suggests that it is somehow ‘fair’ for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">laimant solicitors to shoulder the high financial burden of covering all the costs up to permission because they should be able to reliably predict the outcome regardless</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> of all these factors. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.04pt; padding-left:2.96pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The second example is another settled case, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">C v </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which was legally aided. The Claimant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">had been convicted whilst in the military of having a gay partner. A challenge was brought to the Rehabilitation of Offenders (Exceptions) Ord</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">er.  It was successfully argued that the requirement to disclose previous spent convictions to employers should not apply to those who had been convicted of discriminatory offences under Section 13 of the Sexual Offenders Act 1956.  The case never re</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ached </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">permission stage as the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Mo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">J</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> agreed to bring forward changes to their legislation and the amendment subsequently came in via the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012.  Had this case not been initiate it is possible that the changes to the law would have taken mu</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ch longer and yet, as it never reached permission we would not, under the proposal, have received </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">unless discretion was exercised at the very end of the case. In all likelihood this case would never have been taken. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The comparison with applicati</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ons for permission to the Upper Tribunal (where this system of funding operates) is not appropriate, since in those cases the provider is much more likely to have been involved at first instance and will have a fully reasoned decision to consider.  This me</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ans both that it is easier to make a reliable assessment of the merits and that the workload in preparing an application for permission to appeal will be correspondingly less. Such cases will also not involve the gathering and consideration of any new evid</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ence, as their sole focus is the reasoned decision of the lower court. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.56pt; padding-left:3.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The consultation assumes that costs will be recovered from the defendant i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> there is a settlement after proceedings are issued. This is wrong. They may be, but </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">f the settlement is any</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">thing less than what the claimant sought in the claim form, or there is some new event before the permission stage is reached, claimant solicitors will very often not be awarded costs – it is all too frequent in such cases that each side bears its own cost</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s unless a case is entirely clear cut.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.05pt; padding-left:2.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The consultation ignores the phenomenon of the Administrative Court’s practice of holding ‘rolled up’ permission and merits hearings where merits are unclear or the case is urgent. In effect, these cases proceed direc</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t to trial, even though permission has not been granted. If a rolled up hearing is directed, it will put the whole of the costs of the case at risk, in effect turning Legal Aid funding into a conditional fee agreement with no uplift</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and vastly reduced hour</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ly rates</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. The costs consequences of this happening in any case for the solicitor and Counsel will mean pursuing such cases is unrealistic. Yet the court has decided, in making directions for a rolled up hearing, that they are properly brought (otherwise </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">pe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rmission would have been refused) and merit full consideration. There is value in such hearings, not least to reduce delay, but they will be resisted in future if the proposal is implemented.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 66.18pt; padding-left:5.82pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The proposal assumes there is currently no mechanism to deal w</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ith ‘cases that never should have been brought’, but that is incorrect. Given the recent response to the last consultation on judicial review, it may be thought appropriate to propose that costs might be denied only in cases where a judge certifies – and h</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e or she will have to consider in future – that the application for permission was wholly without merit.  It will also be worth looking at the existing powers of the court to make an order denying a party’s representatives their Legal Aid costs.  For examp</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">le, section 51(6) of the Senior Courts Act 1981 empowers a court to make a wasted costs order, which can include disallowing the whole or part of any wasted costs incurred as a result of any improper, unreasonable or negligent act or omission on the part o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">f any legal or other representative.  Such orders are occasionally made.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The proposal is wholly impractical  </span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The direct result of the no pre permission costs proposal will be solicitors firms and barristers dealing with judicial review cases in one of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> two ways. Neither serves the Government’s aims or the public interest. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The first likely outcome of the proposal will impact on what the Government considers to be ‘stronger’ cases, i.e. those where a grant of permission is predictable provided the case g</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ets that far.  In these cases there may or may not be a settlement including payment of costs if the claim is issued, but the only certainty for the solicitor </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">or barrister is that substantial work may be undertaken with no remuneration at all. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">It follows t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hat obtaining permission </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">once a claim is issued </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">will become a key objective, rather than resolving the case at the earliest possible stage. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">his will: </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">eliminate all ADR (mediation, round table discussions etc) </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">post-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">issue in legally aided cases; </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">discourag</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e settlement after claims are issued but before permission is granted, unless costs are paid by agreement; and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">generate satellite costs litigation in which claimants ask the court to grant permission and award costs simply in order to ensure that they are</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> paid. </span></li></ol><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The net result will be</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">more of the cases in th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is group being issued, not less,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> more ta</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ken forward rather than settled,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> more inter </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> costs sought and ord</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ered against public authorities</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and more Court time taken up with the associated decision making. The costs savings anticipated by the proposal will undoubtedly be cancelled out. The most likely net result wi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ll be increased costs overall. Once claims are issued, t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">he judicial review proc</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ess will become extremely confrontational, rather than co-operative as</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> is meant to be. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The second likely consequence of the proposal is that it will have a significant chilling effect on applications for permission in the remaining cases: those </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">where a solicitor cannot be sure to a very high standard that permission will be granted or a sett</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">lement with costs reached. The effect will be to build in an extra, pre-emptive, level of protection for public authorities: over and above the requirement to obtain permission before bringing the claim (which applies to no area of private law litigation),</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> providers will be penalised if they bring cases which (for whatever reason) do not secure permission. That protection is entirely inappropriate. It undermines the rule of law and accountability. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Wrong in principle  </span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> With these proposals, the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">is effectively seeking to make it more difficult for people to challenge their decisions, placing on lawyers what is an impossible burden. This amounts to a fundamental assault on the rule of law, which cannot be justified by reference to evidence, or even</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> the proposed savings. The harm this will cause is entirely disproportionate to the negligible savings.  </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Proposal to end all funding for ‘borderline’ test cases</span></h2><ol start="68" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The Government intends to press on with removing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Legal Aid for all cases assessed as having “b</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">orderline” prospects of success</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This proposal is also impractical and wrong in principle. Again, we will take these issues in turn.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Practical implications </span></p><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">In common with many aspects of this consultation, the proposals concerning borderline cases a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> form</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ulated are not supported by clear evidence.  This provision is supposed to remove 100 cases from the system and so save the state just £1million. The Civil Legal Aid Credibility Impact Assessment fails to explain how these figures are reached. Still less i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s there any attempt to grapple with:  </span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">the cost of miscarriages of justice</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">poor practices which may go unchallenged</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> when this objective is achieved; and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">delays and adjournments of hearings caused by desperate claimants pursuing their cases as litiga</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">nts in person. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Those who are utterly desperate and are struggling to access services such as lifesaving medication that is being refused, adapted accommodation, or the right to die with dignity, may well do so. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Presumably the government will still be repre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sented by a team of expert lawyers in such cases at tax payers’ expense. Yet anecdotal evidence suggests Treasury Panel and court costs would be reduced by having a competent lawyer representing the claimant. That is underpinned by the experience of the Fa</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">mily Courts (see above).   </span></li></ol><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The Impact Assessment </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">accompanying the original proposals </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">also suggests that some of the ‘borderline’ cases would be resolved by ADR or funded their case privately. These assumptions are fanciful</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">First, even with the best pre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">pared case and strongest grounds, despite </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Cowl</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> principles it is incredibly difficult to get defendant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">public bodies to the table to talk. It usually takes the pressure of a judicial review application being issued, or</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">indeed,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> hearing being listed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> before a defendant will be prepared to mediate or enter into a roundtable meeting. Usually, they prefer to wait and see what happens. With no litigation pressure to focus the public bodies’ mind, there is no way they will be prepared to consider an altern</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ative or settle what might often be an entirely reasonable claim. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Second, i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">n legally aided cases mediation and other forms of ADR are currently funded using full representation funding pre permission. That funding is to be removed altogether in judicial r</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">eview cases (see above). </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Last, it is irrational to suggest that those who currently qualify for Legal Aid would simply be able to fund a case privately, let alone face the associated adverse costs risk. It should also be born in mind that seismic changes </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">to CFAs came into force in April 2013 which mean that firms will not be able to simply bring meritorious claims on CFAs and take the risk.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Eliminating funding for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">genuine </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">test cases is wrong in principle</span></p><ol start="71" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">‘Borderline cases’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">often constitute seminal test cas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">es in which the courts have clarified some of the most difficult issues, for example the right to die with dignity, the ban on gay people serving in the army, systemic abuse by armed forces, and whether soldiers serving overseas should be protected by the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Human Rights Act. In a jurisdiction without a written Constitution or codified laws, and in which law is thus based on and developed through case law, such test cases are an essential part of the legal system. Challenging the status quo inevitably means th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e merits are not going to be easily predicted, and some cases need to be appealed before an authoritative decision emerges. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">These cases often, by definition, can benefit many thousands of people – and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in practice do so,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> as many succeed. In cost benefit te</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rms they often represent better value for public money than litigation focussed on a single dispute. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Impact of the proposal, if implemented</span></p><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Below are examples of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> cases</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> ‘borderline prospects of success’ in which this firm has represented the claimant. The public interest in the litigation proceeding could not be clearer, but</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> this proposal is implemented</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> similar cases will not be </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">funded:</span></li></ol><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.82pt; padding-left:3.18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (Purdy) –v- the Director of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> Public Prosecutions</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2009] UKHL 45. Debbie Purdy is a woman in her late 40s suffering from Multiple Sclerosis who wished to establish whether her husband was likely to be prosecuted if he assisted her and travelled to Switzerland when she decides to have </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">an assisted death. The House of Lords found that the Director of Public Prosecutions was required as a matter of law under the principles of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">foreseeability</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> and accessibility of the law to publish guidelines which set out the factors that he would take into</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> account in deciding whether to prosecute or not under the Suicide Act 1961 so that subjects could regulate their behaviour accordingly. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">This is a classi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> example of a test case, the merits of which are by definition borderline. The wider public benefit of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> clarifying this area of the law for the general public cannot be overstated. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Nicklinson</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> and L) –v- MOJ and others</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> - Case </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Nos</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">: C1/2012/2712 CO/774/2010 HQ11X04443. In this ongoing test case with wider public benefit, Paul Lamb and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Jane </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Nicklinson</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> have</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> appealed against the Divisional Court’s decision to dismiss applications by Tony </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Nicklinson</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> that the current law of murder and assisted suicide contravenes his Article 8 ECHR rights, as a disabled person wishing to die with dignity at a moment of his choo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sing.  The appeal hearing had been heard and judgement is awaited.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> The cases raise issue of wide public importance.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> As a result of these cases, recent</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">YouGov</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> polls show that 70-80% of the public believe that the current suicide laws are outdated</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and need</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> to be changed. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.49pt; padding-left:3.51pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Savage –v- South Essex Partnership NHS Trust</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2008] UKHL 74. The Claimant in this case brought a claim under Article 2 of the European Convention on Human Rights against the NHS Trust. Anna’s mother had been detained under Section 3 of the Mental Health Act 1983 and had managed to walk a mile and a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">half to a station and to throw herself under a train. The case established the principle, that the hospital owed a specific duty of care to a detained patient, namely that where there is</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a real and immediate risk to life, then the Trust must take all reas</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">onable steps to avert that risk, otherwise they will be liable for a breach of the Art 2 duty. This is reassuring for all families and should ultimately improve standards in mental health hospitals which few would argue against.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.17pt; padding-left:2.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (JL) –v- Secretary of Sta</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">te for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2008] UKHL 68. This case involved a vulnerable prisoner who attempted suicide by hanging whilst in Feltham Youth Offenders Institution. He survived, having suffered brain damage. The case concerned the investigate obligation und</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">er Article 2 ECHR.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> The case established the scope and extent of the duty to investigate by the state, when things go wrong, in circumstances where the state has taken away a subject’s liberty. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.04pt; padding-left:2.96pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">FB –v- DPP</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2007] EWHC 28. FB, a patient who suffered from me</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ntal illness sought to challenge the DPP’s withdrawal of a prosecution against the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Defendant who had assaulted FB, including biting off his ear. The prosecution was dropped on the grounds that FB’s evidence would not be reliable due to his mental illness. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">FB was successful in his challenge by way of judicial review of this decision that the DPP acted irrationally, unlawfully in dropping the prosecution. This was the first time that such a claim had been bought in these circumstances. One might think such a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">case was likely to restore victims’ confidence in the justice system more broadly. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (TB) acting by the Official Solicitor –v- Stafford Crown Court</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2006] EWHC 14645. TB, a 14 year old </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">child</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, had been sexually assaulted. The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">alleged perpetrator</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> sought dis</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">closure of her confidential medical records in order to discredit her evidence. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Saimo</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Chahal</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> intervened on behalf of the Official Solicitor in the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">criminal case, but the judge refused to consider the victim’s application.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> In a claim for judicial review of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> that decision, the court found that the Crown Court had acted unlawfully in breach of TB’s Article 8 rights and failed to secure her rights. The case led to a precedent being set for the use of exceptional funding for representation for victims in Crown C</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ourt cases where</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">defendant </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">seeks disclosure of confidential medical information. The case also led to a change in the Criminal Procedures Rules ensuring that victims have the right to notice when an application is being made for disclosure of their sensi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">tive medical information.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 68.56pt; padding-left:3.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (J) –v- </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Southend</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> DC</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2005] EWCH </span><span style="color:#343434; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">3457 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">(Admin). Four Claimants with </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Downs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> Syndrome challenged </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Southend</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> District C</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ouncil</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> which operated a day centre</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">for learning disabled adults.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ouncil argued that it did not owe any duty und</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">er Community Care legislation or Articles 8 and 14 ECHR for long term users of the Day Centre who were not ordinarily resident in the catchment area. Upon the issue of judicial review proceedings, the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">ouncil agreed to re-assess the needs of the centre use</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">rs</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">and to provide appropriate services. Such people would be without a remedy if these proposals were introduced and such poor decision making would go unchallenged. This cannot be a good thing for society generally. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 69.05pt; padding-left:2.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">R (Stephens) –v- Plymouth City Council</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> [2002] EWCH </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> 388. Mrs Stephen</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, a learning disabled young man’s mother,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sought access to his medical records in order to address issues about his care and whether a Guardianship Order should be continued. The court found that although there was a legit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">imate interest in protecting the confidentially and personal information about a person in the Guardianship of the local authority, his mother</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">, who was his nearest</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> relative</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> was entitled to have direct access to that information in order to determine wheth</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">er she should oppose the renewal of the Guardianship Application and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">in order to determine what was in the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">his</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> best interest.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></p><ol start="74" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">Legal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">id is not a welfare benefit; it is an equalising measure. Its aim is to ensure that everyone subject to UK juri</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">sdiction can enjoy their rights in a meaningful way through access legal advice when it would otherwise be unaffordable and representation funded to the extent necessary to ensure that the merits of any court case will determine the outcome, rather than th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e relative wealth or power of the opposing parties. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; list-style-position:inside; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 27pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">These fundamental principles remain shamelessly compromised by the Government's proposals. They are ill-considered, hasty and reckless. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">hey will be hugely costly. And they will create a silenced minorit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> whose cases will never be heard by our courts, regardless of their merits or what </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">k</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">7 September </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2013</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">These are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">summarised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> in an article by Mike </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Schwarcz</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> and John </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Halford</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> of this firm: </span><a href="http://www.solicitorsjournal.com/comment/legal-aid-cuts-more-detail-more-devils"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.solicitorsjournal.com/comme</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">nt/legal-aid-cuts-more-detail-more-devils</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/features/interview-chris-grayling</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">R v. Secretary of State for the Home Department ex parte </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Khawaj</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> [1984] AC74 at 111G</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20091009075030/http://www.justice.gov.uk/consultations/legal-aid-refocusing-priority-cases.htm</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> The abandoned 2008 residence test would not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">excluded EU nationals from accessing legal aid (regardless of where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">they are resident) or others covered by reciprocal arrangements. It would not have affected cases concerning immigration issues (about entry or terms of stay), nor the detention of any client under the Mental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Heath</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Act 1983, nor childcare or supervision pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">oceedings under the Children Act 1989, nor child abduction proceedings covered by the Hague Convention, nor domestic violence proceedings, and nor would it cover housing proceedings where the client was at risk of homelessness. The 2008 consultation paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">accepted, without much elaboration, that it would not be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">‘appropriate’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> to leave work of this kind unfunded.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.gov.uk/publications/corporate-reports/legal-services-commission"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.gov.uk/publications/corporate-r</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">eports/legal-services-commission</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/helping-and-supporting-victims-of-crime</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">See </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">Article 2, and CEDAW</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">General Recommendation 28</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">Paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">. 32,34,36; HRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">General Comment No. 31</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">Paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt">. 15-20.</span></p></body></html>